\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11959078 RL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 Oh well - well only the council}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5532069\charrsid2756420 l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 ors I suppose, that's all, you know, district councillors. That's all, they were coming up. There were no big families here. It was just the Squire Lewis - we called - as we knew him then, b
ut lived practically in Ton Gwynlais you see. In Green Meadow. Oh there was a - there was a stipend}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5532069\charrsid2756420 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 ary - stipend}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5532069\charrsid2756420 i}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 ary - Will - Williams I think the name was, used to live at - Plas Lan you know. Used to know him, he used to go to the - back and forward in 
a coach, I think Tong - Pontypridd I think he's - worked at. And - that's the - opposite the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5532069\charrsid2756420 vicariate}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 
 where it's all houses now, you see, it was one big house, one house there you see. That went. No, there was no - no - like - squire sort of person, anyon
e above the average, there was - 'course business - because with a lot of people - smaller business people come out here you see. Well - now for instance, the - biggest person that way - like you say would be the manager of the works, there was Robert Dav
ies, manager of Mellon Griffith works, and then there was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11162986 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 He lived in Whitchurch did he?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11959078 RL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 
Yes. Yes, lived just beyond - the biggest house just beyond the chapel, it - well it will be shops now, just beyond - opposite the church there, Penlyn Ro
ad, and - well oh there was Coal, he came, but that was much later. Well - no, no, it wasn't, it - old - Herbert Coley wasn't it, he's first - first living - Pinner Park, that house, what do they call it, Treoda isn't it? Well - not Plas Treoda, Treoda, t
h
at was it just called Treoda, well he lived - first of all he lived there. And then he - he built Coleytown. Because he was a big coal owner you see. That was I suppose he would be the next after squire Lewis, came on you see. But he didn't enter into the
 life of the village so much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11162986 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 Squire Lewis did enter into the life of the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11959078 RL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 
Oh yes, he was - old - old fashioned - old fashioned squire really you see. He had the hounds there for a while. Pentarch hounds they are now, I don't know what they were then. That was going to Tongwynlais so much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11162986 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 Whitchurch and Tongwynlais was very much sort of one wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11959078 RL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 Well we are one parish you see. YES? it's - the parish in - included half - the old parish line used to go through the middle of
 Tongwynlais, you see, when we had elections they all had to - had to go up there, own little polling - polling station up there you see, from about half of Tongwynlais. - village.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11162986 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 You people that you considered important such as Mr Williams the Stipend}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5532069\charrsid2756420 i}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 ary.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11959078 RL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 There was another person, that's Morgan Rees. Yes, he came on a little later you know. He came on -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11162986 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 Before the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11959078 RL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 Yes. Oh yes, before the first world war. Or no it was - well about that time I should think, I don't re
member him before but of course I wasn't always about you see. But I remember the Excelsior Rope works - start - setting up, you see. Lewis and Morgan Rees.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11162986 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 He was a manufacturer really then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11959078 RL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 Yes, a rope - wire rope works, he lived there in Whitchurch, at the end of Church Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11162986 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 Why do you think these people were considered important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11959078 RL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 
Well, he was in politics a bit you see, Morgan Rees. And - they were - 'cos there's a big coal owner, Coles were big coal people you see. You see. 'Cos t
hey came up with - you know, as they made money you see. They were - they were not old families like that you see. It was - the docks people come out to here to live as they were - could afford to, and put up these big houses and that you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11162986 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 The land was available here for them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11959078 RL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 Oh yes, plenty of land, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11162986 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 What about the shopkeepers then, who did they associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11959078 RL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11162986 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 You said you thought your family mixed with these?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11959078 RL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 Well a bit, there was - that's right. As far as m
ixing, well my father was only with the council you see, sort of Bill Evans - Bill Evans the grocer we used to call him, Mr Tom Evans the builder, you see, we knew them like that in those days. Or Days - Days were not - he never got into any - they were a
n
d Curls. We knew - we knew the bakers and grocers and things like that about here you see. But you see the only people sometimes - we as a family mixed with the chapel people. That's the only ones I can say we knew, my father being on the council the boro
ugh council you see, local parish councils and - district council and school board you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11162986 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 What about the clergy in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11959078 RL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 Well - 'course the non-conformist ministers - of course there was a - the - there was a bigger difference between the
 Cath - the church - and non-conformists then. Oh quite a bit. Well they didn't mix you see. They had nothing much to do with each other. They hadn't on - not 'til quite recently.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11162986 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 Why was that do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11959078 RL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 Well it was just - dissent that's all,
 just - I mean they always were - always were different you see, they used to preach against each other, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11162986 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 It was like that when you were a boy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11959078 RL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 When I was young, yes, my - I remember the first minister I remember him in Bethel, John Arthur Jones, he was always preaching a}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5532069\charrsid2756420 gainst - what he called sussoto}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 
talism you see, which was just the church ceremonies and things like that you see. That was a great point with him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11162986 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 Why do you think the clergymen mixed with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11959078 RL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 Oh their own people,
 that's all, yes, really. Yes, they never went with the life of the parish more than their own church, no. No, I never knew - hardly knew them you see as a boy growing up. I knew boys who went to church, but the vicar we never saw or heard of him, we didn
'
t. 'Cos - the first time I ever heard one - was one - it was a - the priest meetings, I think it was after the first world war, and they had a kind of big united meeting, and I think the vicar was there you see, that's about the only time I ever saw him, 
the old chap walking up in the street you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11162986 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 What about the non-conformist ministers then, did they enter more into the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11959078 RL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 Oh yes. YES? THEY WERE more in politics, particularly - the Liberal party you see in those days. 'Cos the - the es
tablishment was a big question then you see. This was before the first world war you see. And so they were on - and so of course that kept to the art very largely you see. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11162986 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 There would be some farmers around here then probably?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11959078 RL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 Oh yes. Yes, 
was a few, Phillips the farm across the road. And he was a big man - in - in Bura, that chapel you see. And then there was - Samuel, Tom Samuel, the Village Farm. Righ where the post office is now that farm house was. In fact that bit of wall in front of 
i
t I think is still part of the same boundary walls, yes. And - a friend of course, he married a - a girl that was a friend of my sister's who was living with us at the time, staying with us for a few years, and she married that Tom Samuel. And he was a bi
g - singing man. He had a - a male voice choir here and they came - I think it was second or third in - in the National one year. I forget oh - what year, but I would only be a boy, schoolboy anyway, at the time, old Tom Samuel. Tom Samuel.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11162986 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7538088\charrsid2756420 Who would the farmers associate with?
